[
  {
    "id": "CHEM-JAMB-0001",
    "question": "X is crystalline salt of sodium. Solution of X in water turns litmus red produces a gas which turns lime water milky when added to sodium carbonate. With barium chloride solution, X gives a white precipitate which is insoluble in dilute hydrochloric acid. X is",
    "options": [
      "Na2CO3",
      "NaHCO3",
      "NaHSO4",
      "Na2SO3",
      "Na2SO4"
    ],
    "answer": 2,
    "exam": [
      "JAMB"
    ],
    "level": "medium",
    "topic": "Acids, Bases & Salts",
    "marks": 2,
    "explanation": "The solution turns litmus red, indicating acidity, which rules out Na2CO3 and NaHCO3 (basic salts). When X is added to sodium carbonate, it produces a gas that turns lime water milky; this gas is CO2, confirming that X is an acid stronger than carbonic acid. NaHSO4 (sodium hydrogen sulfate) is acidic and reacts with carbonate to release CO2. The white precipitate with BaCl2 that is insoluble in dilute HCl confirms the presence of sulfate ions (SO4^2-), not sulfite (SO3^2-). NaHSO4 contains sulfate and is acidic, matching all observations.",
    "hint": "Look for an acidic sodium salt that contains sulfate and releases CO2 from carbonate.",
    "timeLimit": 45,
    "year": 1983,
    "tags": [
      "chemistry",
      "salt analysis",
      "inorganic chemistry",
      "jamb"
    ],
    "requiresCalculator": false,
    "calculatorType": "none",
    "formula": "",
    "constants": {},
    "createdBy": "OAE Admin",
    "lastUpdated": "2026-04-05"
  },
  {
    "id": "CHEM-JAMB-0002",
    "question": "The alkanol obtained from the production of soap is",
    "options": [
      "ethanol",
      "glycerol",
      "methanol",
      "propanol",
      "glycol"
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "exam": [
      "JAMB"
    ],
    "level": "easy",
    "topic": "Organic Chemistry",
    "marks": 1,
    "explanation": "Soap is produced by the saponification of fats and oils (triglycerides) with a strong base such as sodium hydroxide. This hydrolysis reaction breaks the ester bonds in triglycerides, yielding soap (fatty acid salts) and glycerol (propane-1,2,3-triol). Glycerol is the alkanol (triol) obtained as a byproduct.",
    "hint": "Remember the byproduct of soap making is a sweet triol.",
    "timeLimit": 30,
    "year": 1983,
    "tags": [
      "chemistry",
      "saponification",
      "organic chemistry",
      "jamb"
    ],
    "requiresCalculator": false,
