    ],
    "level": "easy",
    "topic": "Practical Chemistry: Flame Types",
    "marks": 1,
    "explanation": "Welding and cutting of metals require a flame with a very high temperature. The oxy-acetylene flame, produced by combusting acetylene (C2H2) in pure oxygen, reaches approximately 3500°C, making it suitable for metalworking. 'Cotton metals' is likely a typographical error for 'cutting metals'. Acetylene alone burns with a sooty, lower-temperature flame; oxygen is required to achieve welding temperatures.",
    "hint": "Welders use a mixture of a fuel gas and pure oxygen.",
    "timeLimit": 30,
