  {
    "id": "CHEM-JAMB-0004",
    "question": "Consecutive members of an alkane homologous series differ by",
    "options": [
      "CH",
      "CH2",
      "CH3",
      "CnHn",
      "CnH2n+2"
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "exam": [
      "JAMB"
    ],
    "level": "easy",
    "topic": "Organic Chemistry",
    "marks": 1,
    "explanation": "Alkanes are saturated hydrocarbons with the general formula CnH2n+2. In a homologous series, each successive member differs from the previous one by a constant increment of a methylene group (-CH2-). For example, methane (CH4) and ethane (C2H6) differ by CH2.",
    "hint": "Look for the repeating unit in the carbon chain.",
    "timeLimit": 30,
    "year": 1983,
    "tags": [
      "chemistry",
      "homologous series",
      "alkanes",
      "organic chemistry",
      "jamb"
    ],
