  {
    "id": "CHEM-JAMB-0005",
    "question": "If an element has the electronic configuration 1s2 2s2 2p6 3s2 3p2, it is",
    "options": [
      "a metal",
      "an alkaline earth metal",
      "an s-block element",
      "a p-block element",
      "a transition element"
    ],
    "answer": 3,
    "exam": [
      "JAMB"
    ],
    "level": "easy",
    "topic": "Atomic Structure",
    "marks": 1,
    "explanation": "The given configuration ends in 3p2, meaning the highest energy electron occupies the p-subshell. Elements with their outermost electron in a p-orbital are classified as p-block elements. This configuration corresponds to silicon (atomic number 14), which is in Group IVA (Group 14) of the p-block. It is not an s-block element, alkaline earth metal, or transition metal.",
    "hint": "The last subshell determines the block.",
    "timeLimit": 30,
    "year": 1983,
    "tags": [
      "chemistry",
      "electronic configuration",
      "periodic table",
      "jamb"
    ],
    "requiresCalculator": false,
    "calculatorType": "none",
    "formula": "",
    "constants": {},
    "createdBy": "OAE Admin",
    "lastUpdated": "2026-04-05"
  },
  {
    "id": "CHEM-JAMB-0006",
    "question": "Some copper (II) sulphate pentahydrate (CuSO4.5H2O), was heated at 120°C with the following results: Wt of crucible = 10.00 g; Wt of crucible + CuSO4.5H2O = 14.98g; Wt of crucible + residue = 13.54g. How many molecules of water of crystallization were lost? [H=1, Cu=63.5, O=16, S=32]",
    "options": [
      "1",
      "2",
      "3",
      "4",
      "5"
    ],
    "answer": 2,
    "exam": [
      "JAMB"
    ],
    "level": "hard",
    "topic": "Acids, Bases & Salts",
    "marks": 2,
    "explanation": "Mass of hydrate = 14.98g - 10.00g = 4.98g. Mass of anhydrous salt = 13.54g - 10.00g = 3.54g. Mass of water lost = 4.98g - 3.54g = 1.44g. Molar mass of CuSO4 = 63.5 + 32 + (16×4) = 159.5 g/mol. Moles of CuSO4 = 3.54g / 159.5 g/mol = 0.0222 mol. Molar mass of H2O = 18 g/mol. Moles of H2O lost = 1.44g / 18 g/mol = 0.08 mol. Ratio of moles H2O lost to moles CuSO4 = 0.08 / 0.0222 ≈ 3.6. Since the salt is pentahydrate (5 H2O), and approximately 3 molecules were lost, 2 molecules remain. The question asks how many were lost, so answer is 3.",
    "hint": "Calculate water lost, then moles ratio.",
    "timeLimit": 90,
    "year": 1983,
    "tags": [
      "chemistry",
      "hydrates",
      "stoichiometry",
      "calculation",
      "jamb"
    ],
    "requiresCalculator": true,
    "calculatorType": "basic",
    "formula": "n = m/M",
    "constants": {
      "H": 1,
      "Cu": 63.5,
      "O": 16,
      "S": 32
    },
    "createdBy": "OAE Admin",
    "lastUpdated": "2026-04-05"
  },
  {
    "id": "CHEM-JAMB-0007",
    "question": "The three-dimensional shape of methane is",
    "options": [
      "hexagonal",
      "trigonal",
      "linear",
      "tetrahedral",
      "cubical"
    ],
    "answer": 3,
    "exam": [
      "JAMB"
    ],
    "level": "easy",
    "topic": "Chemical Bonding",
    "marks": 1,
    "explanation": "Methane (CH4) has a central carbon atom bonded to four hydrogen atoms with no lone pairs. According to Valence Shell Electron Pair Repulsion (VSEPR) theory, four bonding pairs arrange themselves as far apart as possible, resulting in a tetrahedral geometry with bond angles of approximately 109.5°.",
    "hint": "Four bonds, no lone pairs = tetrahedral.",
    "timeLimit": 30,
    "year": 1983,
    "tags": [
      "chemistry",
      "vsepr",
      "molecular geometry",
      "methane",
      "jamb"
    ],
    "requiresCalculator": false,
    "calculatorType": "none",
    "formula": "",
    "constants": {},
    "createdBy": "OAE Admin",
    "lastUpdated": "2026-04-05"
  },
  {
    "id": "CHEM-JAMB-0008",
    "question": "An unknown organic compound X has a relative molecular mass of 180. It is a colourless crystalline solid, readily soluble in water. X contains the element C, H, and O in the atomic ratio 1:2:1. The compound has a sweet taste and melts on heating. In the presence of yeast and in the absence of air X is converted to compound Y and a colourless gas. Compound Y reacts with sodium metal to produce a gas Z which gives a 'pop' sound with a glowing splint. Y also reacts with ethanoic acid to give a sweet smelling compound W. Compound W is",
    "options": [
      "a soap",
      "an oil",
      "an alkane",
      "an ester",
      "sucrose"
    ],
    "answer": 3,
    "exam": [
      "JAMB"
    ],
    "level": "medium",
    "topic": "Organic Chemistry",
    "marks": 2,
    "explanation": "From the description, X is glucose (C6H12O6, RMM = 180, C:H:O ratio 1:2:1). Fermentation of glucose by yeast produces ethanol (Y) and CO2. Ethanol reacts with sodium to release hydrogen gas (Z, pop sound). Ethanol reacts with ethanoic acid in an esterification reaction to form ethyl ethanoate (W), which is a sweet-smelling ester. Soaps are salts of fatty acids, oils are triglycerides, alkanes are hydrocarbons, and sucrose is a disaccharide; none fit the esterification product.",
    "hint": "The sweet-smelling product from alcohol + carboxylic acid is an ester.",
    "timeLimit": 45,
    "year": 1983,
    "tags": [
      "chemistry",
      "fermentation",
      "esterification",
      "organic chemistry",
      "jamb"
    ],
    "requiresCalculator": false,
    "calculatorType": "none",
    "formula": "",
    "constants": {},
    "createdBy": "OAE Admin",
    "lastUpdated": "2026-04-05"
  },
  {
    "id": "CHEM-JAMB-0009",
    "question": "An unknown organic compound X has a relative molecular mass of 180. It is a colourless crystalline solid, readily soluble in water. X contains the element C, H, and O in the atomic ratio 1:2:1. The compound has a sweet taste and melts on heating. In the presence of yeast and in the absence of air X is converted to compound Y and a colourless gas. Compound Y reacts with sodium metal to produce a gas Z which gives a 'pop' sound with a glowing splint. Y also reacts with ethanoic acid to give a sweet smelling compound W. The molecular formula of X is",
    "options": [
      "C12H22O11",
      "C6H12O6",
      "C3H6O3",
      "C7H14O7",
      "C4H8O4"
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "exam": [
      "JAMB"
    ],
    "level": "medium",
    "topic": "Organic Chemistry",
    "marks": 2,
    "explanation": "The empirical formula from the ratio C:H:O = 1:2:1 gives (CH2O)n. The empirical formula mass = 12 + 2 + 16 = 30 g/mol. Relative molecular mass is given as 180. n = 180 / 30 = 6. Therefore, the molecular formula is (CH2O)6 = C6H12O6. C12H22O11 is sucrose (RMM 342), C3H6O3 is lactic acid (RMM 90), and the others do not match the RMM of 180. Glucose and fructose are C6H12O6, fitting all properties described.",
    "hint": "Divide the molecular mass by the empirical formula mass.",
    "timeLimit": 60,
    "year": 1983,
    "tags": [
      "chemistry",
      "empirical formula",
      "molecular formula",
      "organic chemistry",
      "jamb"
    ],
    "requiresCalculator": true,
    "calculatorType": "basic",
    "formula": "n = Molar mass / Empirical formula mass",
    "constants": {
      "C": 12,
      "H": 1,
      "O": 16
    },
    "createdBy": "OAE Admin",
    "lastUpdated": "2026-04-05"
  },
  {
    "id": "CHEM-JAMB-0010",
    "question": "An unknown organic compound X has a relative molecular mass of 180. It is a colourless crystalline solid, readily soluble in water. X contains the element C, H, and O in the atomic ratio 1:2:1. The compound has a sweet taste and melts on heating. In the presence of yeast and in the absence of air X is converted to compound Y and a colourless gas. Compound Y reacts with sodium metal to produce a gas Z which gives a 'pop' sound with a glowing splint. Y also reacts with ethanoic acid to give a sweet smelling compound W. Reaction of X with yeast forms the basis of the",
