    "constants": {},
    "createdBy": "OAE Admin",
    "lastUpdated": "2026-04-05"
  },
  {
    "id": "CHEM-JAMB-0012",
    "question": "Which of the following relationships between the pressure P, the volume V and the temperature T, represents an ideal gas behavior?",
    "options": [
      "P & VT",
      "P & T/V",
      "PT & V",
      "PV & VT",
      "P & V/T"
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "exam": [
      "JAMB"
    ],
    "level": "easy",
    "topic": "Acids, Bases & Salts",
    "marks": 1,
    "explanation": "The ideal gas equation is PV = nRT. Rearranging, P = (nR)T/V. Since n and R are constants, pressure (P) is directly proportional to temperature (T) and inversely proportional to volume (V). Therefore, P ∝ T/V. This is the correct relationship representing ideal gas behavior.",
    "hint": "From PV = nRT, solve for P.",
    "timeLimit": 30,
    "year": 1983,
    "tags": [
      "chemistry",
      "ideal gas law",
      "gas laws",
      "jamb"
    ],
    "requiresCalculator": false,
    "calculatorType": "none",
    "formula": "PV = nRT",
    "constants": {},
    "createdBy": "OAE Admin",
    "lastUpdated": "2026-04-05"
  },
