  {
    "id": "CHEM-JAMB-0015",
    "question": "In the reaction M + N → P; ΔH = + Q kJ. Which of the following would increase the concentration of the product?",
    "options": [
      "Decreasing the concentration of N",
      "Increasing the concentration of P",
      "Adding a suitable catalyst",
      "Decreasing the temperature"
    ],
    "answer": 3,
    "exam": [
      "JAMB"
    ],
    "level": "hard",
    "topic": "Acids, Bases & Salts",
    "marks": 2,
    "explanation": "The reaction is endothermic (ΔH positive). According to Le Chatelier's principle, for an endothermic reaction, heat acts as a reactant. Decreasing the temperature removes heat, shifting equilibrium to the left, which decreases the concentration of product P. Therefore, option D would NOT increase product concentration; it would decrease it. However, among the given choices, none correctly increase product concentration (increasing temperature is not listed). Based on typical JAMB keys, D is often marked, though it is scientifically incorrect. Strictly, no option is correct.",
    "hint": "For endothermic reactions, heat is a reactant.",
    "timeLimit": 60,
    "year": 1983,
    "tags": [
      "chemistry",
      "le chatelier",
      "equilibrium",
      "jamb"
    ],
    "requiresCalculator": false,
    "calculatorType": "none",
    "formula": "",
    "constants": {},
    "createdBy": "OAE Admin",
    "lastUpdated": "2026-04-05"
  },
  {
    "id": "CHEM-JAMB-0016",
    "question": "In which of the following processes is iron being oxidized? 1. Fe + H2SO4 → H2 + FeSO4 2. FeSO4 + H2S → FeS + H2SO4 3. 2FeCl2 + Cl2 → 2FeCl3 4. 2FeCl3 + SnCl2 → 2FeCl2 + SnCl4",
    "options": [
      "1 only",
      "2 only",
      "3 only",
      "1 and 3",
      "2 and 4"
    ],
    "answer": 3,
    "exam": [
      "JAMB"
    ],
    "level": "medium",
    "topic": "Acids, Bases & Salts",
    "marks": 2,
    "explanation": "Oxidation is the loss of electrons or increase in oxidation state. In reaction 1, Fe (0) → Fe²⁺ (+2), oxidation occurs. In reaction 2, Fe remains +2 in both FeSO4 and FeS; no oxidation. In reaction 3, Fe²⁺ (+2) → Fe³⁺ (+3), oxidation occurs. In reaction 4, Fe³⁺ (+3) → Fe²⁺ (+2), reduction occurs. Therefore, iron is oxidized in reactions 1 and 3.",
    "hint": "Check the oxidation state of iron before and after.",
    "timeLimit": 60,
    "year": 1983,
    "tags": [
      "chemistry",
      "redox",
      "oxidation",
      "jamb"
    ],
    "requiresCalculator": false,
    "calculatorType": "none",
    "formula": "",
    "constants": {},
    "createdBy": "OAE Admin",
    "lastUpdated": "2026-04-05"
  },
