      "JAMB"
    ],
    "level": "easy",
    "topic": "Acids, Bases & Salts",
    "marks": 1,
    "explanation": "Efflorescence is the process by which a hydrated salt loses its water of crystallization when exposed to air, forming a lower hydrate or becoming anhydrous. Sodium sulphate decahydrate (Glauber's salt) is efflorescent. Hygroscopy is absorption of moisture without dissolving; deliquescence is absorption leading to solution; effervescence is gas evolution; dehydration is removal of water by heating or chemical means.",
    "hint": "Loss of water to air = efflorescence.",
    "timeLimit": 30,
