    "level": "easy",
    "topic": "Metals & Extraction",
    "marks": 1,
    "explanation": "Oil spills on water are commonly treated using dispersants or detergents (surfactants). These chemicals break down the oil into small droplets, which are then more readily biodegraded by microorganisms and dispersed in the water column. Heating, stirring, organic solvents, and cooling are impractical or environmentally harmful methods.",
