  {
    "id": "CHEM-JAMB-0027",
    "question": "In the reactions (1) H2(g) + ½O2(g) → H2O(l); ΔH = -286 kJ (2) C(s) + O2(g) → CO2(g); ΔH = -406 kJ the equations imply that",
    "options": [
      "more heat is absorbed than evolved in (1)",
      "more heat is absorbed in (2)",
      "less heat is evolved in (1)",
      "reaction (2) proceeds faster than (1)",
      "reaction (1) proceeds faster than (2)"
    ],
    "answer": 2,
    "exam": [
      "JAMB"
    ],
    "level": "easy",
    "topic": "Acids, Bases & Salts",
    "marks": 1,
    "explanation": "ΔH values are negative, indicating both reactions are exothermic (heat is evolved). The magnitude of ΔH indicates the amount of heat evolved. For reaction (1), ΔH = -286 kJ, meaning 286 kJ of heat is evolved. For reaction (2), ΔH = -406 kJ, meaning 406 kJ of heat is evolved. Therefore, less heat is evolved in reaction (1) compared to reaction (2). Rate of reaction is not determined by ΔH.",
    "hint": "Negative ΔH = heat evolved. Compare the absolute values.",
    "timeLimit": 30,
    "year": 1983,
    "tags": [
      "chemistry",
      "enthalpy",
      "thermochemistry",
      "jamb"
