  {
    "id": "CHEM-JAMB-0032",
    "question": "Some metals are extracted from their ores after some preliminary treatments by electrolysis (L), some by thermal reaction (T), and some by a combination of both processes (TL). Which set-up in the following for the extraction of iron, copper and aluminum is correct?",
    "options": [
      "Iron (L), copper (L), aluminum (T)",
      "Iron (T), copper (L), aluminum (T)",
      "Iron (TL), copper (TL), aluminum (TL)",
      "Iron (L), copper (T), aluminum (T)",
      "Iron (T), copper (L), aluminum (TL)"
    ],
    "answer": 4,
    "exam": [
      "JAMB"
    ],
    "level": "medium",
    "topic": "Organic Chemistry",
    "marks": 2,
    "explanation": "Iron is extracted by thermal reduction in the blast furnace (T). Copper is purified by electrolysis after smelting (L). Aluminum requires both purification (Bayer process - chemical) and electrolysis (Hall-Héroult) (TL). Therefore, Iron (T), Copper (L), Aluminum (TL) is correct.",
    "hint": "Iron = blast furnace; Copper = electrolytic refining; Aluminum = electrolysis of alumina.",
    "timeLimit": 45,
    "year": 1983,
    "tags": [
