    "id": "CHEM-JAMB-0040",
    "question": "Which of the following solutions will give a white precipitate with barium chloride solution and a green flame test?",
    "options": [
      "Na2SO4",
      "CuSO4",
      "CaSO4",
      "CaCl2",
      "(NH4)2SO4"
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "exam": [
      "JAMB"
    ],
    "level": "medium",
    "topic": "Organic Chemistry",
    "marks": 2,
    "explanation": "Barium chloride test: White precipitate insoluble in dilute HCl indicates sulfate ion. CuSO4 contains SO4²⁻, giving white BaSO4 precipitate. Copper(II) ions impart a blue/green color to the flame. Therefore, CuSO4 matches both properties. Na2SO4 gives white precipitate but sodium flame is yellow. CaSO4 gives white precipitate but calcium flame is brick-red. (NH4)2SO4 gives white precipitate but ammonium gives no flame color.",
    "hint": "Green flame = copper or barium; white precipitate with BaCl2 = sulfate.",
    "timeLimit": 45,
