    "id": "CHEM-JAMB-0043",
    "question": "A jet plane carrying 3,000 kg of ethane burns off all the gas forming water and carbon dioxide. If all the carbon dioxide is expelled and the water formed is condensed and kept on board the plane, then the gain in weight is",
    "options": [
      "1,800 kg",
      "900 kg",
      "600 kg",
      "2,400 kg",
      "1,200 kg"
    ],
    "answer": 3,
    "exam": [
      "JAMB"
    ],
    "level": "hard",
    "topic": "Acids, Bases & Salts",
    "marks": 3,
    "explanation": "Combustion of ethane: 2C2H6 + 7O2 → 4CO2 + 6H2O. Molar mass C2H6 = 30 g/mol, H2O = 18 g/mol. From 60g ethane, 108g water produced. Mass of water from 3000 kg ethane = (108/60) × 3000 = 5400 kg. The ethane (3000 kg) is consumed, CO2 is expelled, water (5400 kg) is kept. Gain in weight = mass of water kept - mass of fuel consumed = 5400 kg - 3000 kg = 2400 kg.",
    "hint": "Gain = mass of water formed - mass of ethane burned.",
    "timeLimit": 90,
    "year": 1983,
    "tags": [
