    "topic": "Acids, Bases & Salts",
    "marks": 1,
    "explanation": "Sodium dioxonitrate(III) is sodium nitrite (NaNO2). The dissolution of most ionic salts in water is exothermic due to hydration of ions releasing more energy than the lattice energy absorbs. Sodium nitrite dissolution is exothermic. The question likely meant 'dissolves in water' and the process is exothermic.",
    "hint": "Most ionic salt dissolutions release heat (exothermic).",
