  {
    "id": "CHEM-JAMB-0047",
    "question": "The equilibrium reaction between copper (I) chloride and chlorine at 25°C and 1 atmosphere is represented by the equation: 2CuCl + Cl2 ⇌ 2CuCl2; ΔH = -166 kJ. Which of the following statement is TRUE for the reaction, pressure remaining constant.",
    "options": [
      "More CuCl2 is formed at 40°C",
      "More CuCl2 is formed at 10°C",
      "Less CuCl2 is formed at 10°C",
      "There is no change in CuCl2 formed at 40°C and 10°C",
      "More CuCl2 is consumed at 40°C"
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "exam": [
      "JAMB"
    ],
    "level": "medium",
    "topic": "Acids, Bases & Salts",
    "marks": 2,
    "explanation": "The reaction has ΔH = -166 kJ, meaning it is exothermic (heat is released). According to Le Chatelier's principle, for an exothermic reaction, decreasing the temperature favors the forward reaction, producing more product (CuCl2). Therefore, more CuCl2 is formed at a lower temperature (10°C) than at a higher temperature (40°C). Option B is correct; E is incorrect because more CuCl2 is formed, not consumed, at lower T.",
    "hint": "Exothermic reaction: lower temperature shifts equilibrium toward products.",
    "timeLimit": 45,
    "year": 1983,
    "tags": [
      "chemistry",
      "equilibrium",
      "le chatelier",
      "exothermic",
      "jamb"
    ],
    "requiresCalculator": false,
    "calculatorType": "none",
    "formula": "",
    "constants": {},
    "createdBy": "OAE Admin",
    "lastUpdated": "2026-04-05"
  },
