  {
    "id": "CHEM-JAMB-0049",
    "question": "Zn + H2SO4 → ZnSO4 + H2. In the above reaction how much zinc will be left undissolved if 2.00 g of zinc treated with 10 cm³ of 1.0 M H2SO4? [Zn = 65, S = 32, O = 16, H = 1]",
    "options": [
      "1.35 g",
      "1.00 g",
      "0.70 g",
      "0.65 g",
      "0.06 g"
    ],
    "answer": 0,
    "exam": [
      "JAMB"
    ],
    "level": "medium",
    "topic": "Acids, Bases & Salts",
    "marks": 2,
    "explanation": "Moles H2SO4 = (1.0 mol/dm³) × (10/1000) dm³ = 0.01 mol. Reaction: Zn + H2SO4 → ZnSO4 + H2, mole ratio 1:1. Moles Zn that react = 0.01 mol. Mass Zn reacted = 0.01 mol × 65 g/mol = 0.65 g. Initial mass Zn = 2.00 g. Mass Zn left undissolved = 2.00 - 0.65 = 1.35 g.",
    "hint": "Find limiting reagent first. Here acid is limiting.",
    "timeLimit": 60,
